-- Malaysia's CIMB drops 4.1 pct on cash call
-- By Yantoultra Ngui
-- Tue Jan 14, 2014 08:08PM EST
-- None



KUALA LUMPUR, Jan 15 (Reuters) - Shares of CIMB Group Holdings Bhd <CIMB.KL> dropped as much as 4.1 percent on Wednesday after Malaysia's second biggest bank by assets raised $1.1 billion through new shares to boost core capital.

The lender, also Southeast Asia's fifth-largest by assets, said on Monday it had issued 500 million shares, or 6.08 percent of its enlarged capital, at 7.10 ringgit each via private placement. [ID:nL3N0KN0K7] The cash call was the biggest in Malaysia since October 2012 when bigger rival Maybank <MBBM.KL> tapped equity markets with a $1.2 billion offering, Thomson Reuters data showed.  CIMB shares were trading at 7 ringgit a share at 0101 GMT, compared with the broader index's <.KLSE> 0.42 percent fall.